TY  - JOUR
T1  - Trade and Capital Flows: A Financial Frictions Perspective
AU  - Antràs, Pol
AU  - Caballero, Ricardo J.
Y1  - 2009/08/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/605583
DO  - 10.1086/605583
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 701
EP  - 744
VL  - 117
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The classical Heckscher?Ohlin?Mundell paradigm states that trade and capital mobility are substitutes in the sense that trade integration reduces the incentives for capital to flow to capital?scarce countries. In this paper we show that in a world with heterogeneous financial development, a very different conclusion emerges. In particular, in less financially developed economies (South), trade and capital mobility are complements in the sense that trade integration increases the return to capital and thus the incentives for capital to flow to South. This interaction implies that deepening trade integration in South raises net capital inflows (or reduces net capital outflows). It also implies that, at the global level, protectionism may backfire if the goal is to rebalance capital flows.
AB  - The classical Heckscher?Ohlin?Mundell paradigm states that trade and capital mobility are substitutes in the sense that trade integration reduces the incentives for capital to flow to capital?scarce countries. In this paper we show that in a world with heterogeneous financial development, a very different conclusion emerges. In particular, in less financially developed economies (South), trade and capital mobility are complements in the sense that trade integration increases the return to capital and thus the incentives for capital to flow to South. This interaction implies that deepening trade integration in South raises net capital inflows (or reduces net capital outflows). It also implies that, at the global level, protectionism may backfire if the goal is to rebalance capital flows.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/605583
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/605583
Y2  - 2024/03/20
